## 2\.3 <a id="_Hlk169959459"></a>Natural Sup\-tRNA

There are various mutations in nature, such as nonsense mutations and frameshift mutations\. These mutations produce abnormal codons, resulting in aberrantl translation  of mRNA\. Concurrently, there are also naturally occurring suppressor tRNAs \(sup\-tRNAs\) in certain species, which can read through abnormal codons and restore protein synthesis\. 

The Natural Sup\-tRNA page catalogs these natural suppressors, which are divided into two modules based on the type of suppression: Nonsense Sup\-tRNA \(decoding nonsense codons\) and Frameshift Sup\-tRNA \(decoding quadruple codons\)\. Each module provides relevant information on sup\-tRNAs, aiming to help users quickly understand a variety of natural sup\-tRNAs and provide reference for the treatment of nonsense mutation related diseases\.

## 2\.3\.1 <a id="_Hlk169983927"></a><a id="_Hlk169967320"></a>Nonsense Sup\-tRNA

The Nonsense Sup tRNA module integrates 300 articles and 50 natural sup\-tRNAs from PubMed and Saccharomyces Genome Database databases, which displays natural sup\-tRNAs information from multiple species such as humans, animals, plants, and microorganisms\. The database compiles 15 categories of information, including 16 species, 3 types of stop codons amber \(UAG\), ochre \(UAA\), opal \(UGA\), 12 non\-canonical amino acids, sup\-tRNA sequences, mutation sites, modified bases\. Users can use keywords such as stop codons, noncanonical charged amino acids, and readthrough mechanism to filter relevant information and complete a rapid search\. This module aims to enhance understanding and research of sup\-tRNAs, helping users to discover more sup\-tRNAs and facilitate the development of new therapeutics\.

## 2\.3\.2 Frameshift Sup\-tRNA

The Frameshift Sup tRNA module integrates 100 articles from the PubMed database and displays sequence information of 50 frameshift sup\-tRNAs\. This module compiles 12 categories of information, including a variety of quadruple codons, 16 noncanonical amino acids, sup\-tRNA sequences, and mutation sites\. Users can filter the required information according to amino acids and quadruple codons for rapid retrieval\.

## 2\.3\.3 Search

This database provides users with an intuitive search interface, allowing users to enter keywords such as codons, species names, or amino acids to search\.

Example: Search for entries with an anticodon after mutation of CUA on the Nonsense page\.

__Step 1：Search__

__![](data:image/png;base64,)__Enter the Nonsense Sup tRNA page, input the search term "CUA" in the search bar, select " anticodon after mutation" in the drop\-down menu to limit the search scope and achieve accurate search\. 

__Step 2：View the results__

![](data:image/png;base64,)Due to the large number of columns, the page displays 4 columns by default\. Users can click on the drop\-down menu and check the information they want to view, such as "anticodon after mutation", then the page will present the contents\. 

The three columns of codon, amino acid, and read\-through mechanism are set up with drop\-down menus\. Users can check the required information as needed and view the filter results after confirmation\.
